# High-Pressure API Test Template

Use this standard sequence for stress-style API validation to keep results comparable run to run.

## 1) Restart + readiness
- Stop existing API process on the target port.
- Start API with explicit env for the run.
- Confirm readiness via health check before testing.

Suggested baseline:
- `kill $(lsof -ti:9000) 2>/dev/null`
- `TEST_MOCK_LLM=true USER_UPDATE_RATE_LIMIT=100 PROGRAM_GENERATION_FOLLOWUP_DELAY_MS=5000 npm start`
- `curl -s http://127.0.0.1:9000/health`

`TEST_MOCK_LLM=true` makes the server return deterministic mock LLM responses so
pressure runs do not spend real OpenAI tokens. Drop it only when you are
explicitly validating live LLM latency/quality (e.g. `openai-load-benchmark`).

## 2) Run configuration
- Use explicit concurrency for pressure runs.
- Decide whether runner-level follow-up is enabled (for isolation, disable it when validating backend-only follow-up).

Examples:
- Backend-only follow-up validation:
  - `ENABLE_TIMEOUT_FOLLOWUP=false node tests/run-initial-prompt-batch.js 8`
- End-to-end resilience (runner + backend):
  - `node tests/run-initial-prompt-batch.js 8`

## 3) Capture and report
- Report pass/fail counts and all generated program IDs.
- For any timeout/failure, include SQL query for `generation_error` and `therapy_response` preview.
- Check server logs for:
  - first-attempt failure,
  - follow-up attempt scheduled,
  - follow-up success or final persisted error.

## 4) Tuning guidance
- If API/rate limiting appears, reduce concurrency first (e.g., 8 -> 6 -> 4).
- If follow-up latency is too high, adjust `PROGRAM_GENERATION_FOLLOWUP_DELAY_MS`.
- Keep one variable change per run so comparisons remain meaningful.
